## Permission System (Critical Architecture)

### 3-Tier Resolution (`HasPermissions` trait)

Permission checks follow this cascade:

```
1. Owner role? → ALWAYS TRUE (bypass all checks)
2. User-level override exists? → Use override (grant=true/deny=false)
3. Role-level default? → Use role's default for this permission
4. None of the above? → FALSE
```

### 48 Permissions in 14 Groups

```
orders.*        → create, view, void, refund
reports.*       → view, sales, inventory, financial, xreport, zreport
inventory.*     → view, manage, categories
menu.*          → view, manage
staff.*         → view, create, update, delete, schedule
finance.*       → view, invoices, expenses, cash_manage, profit_loss
promotions.*    → view, manage, discounts
customers.*     → view, manage, analytics
loyalty.*       → view, manage
reservations.*  → view, manage
delivery.*      → view, manage
devices.*       → view, manage
integrations.*  → xero, webhooks, sms
website.*       → manage
suppliers.*     → view, manage, purchases
```

### Role Defaults (PermissionSeeder)

- **Owner** — All 48 permissions (never checked, always bypassed)
- **Manager** — All except: `staff.create`, `staff.delete`, `devices.manage`, `integrations.xero`, `integrations.webhooks`, `website.manage`
- **Staff** — Limited: `orders.create/view`, `reports.view`, `inventory.view`, `menu.view`, `customers.view`, `suppliers.view`, `delivery.view`, `reservations.view`, `loyalty.view`

### How Permissions Are Enforced

**Backend (middleware):**
```php
// In routes/api.php — every admin route uses permission middleware
Route::get('/staff', [StaffController::class, 'index'])->middleware('permission:staff.view');
Route::post('/staff', [StaffController::class, 'store'])->middleware('permission:staff.create');
```

The `RequirePermission` middleware (`App\Http\Middleware\RequirePermission`):
1. Rejects unauthenticated users (401)
2. Rejects `Customer` model tokens (403) — security boundary
3. Checks `$user->hasPermission($slug)` for each required permission

**Frontend (React):**
```tsx
// App.tsx — Route-level guards
const { can } = usePermissions(user?.id ?? null, user?.role);
<Route path="staff" element={
  <PermissionGuard can={can} permission="staff.view">
    <StaffPage />
  </PermissionGuard>
} />

// Layout.tsx — Nav item filtering
const filteredNavGroups = NAV_GROUPS.map(group => ({
  ...group,
  items: group.items.filter(item => !item.permission || !can || can(item.permission)),
})).filter(group => group.items.length > 0);
```

### Adding a New Permission

1. Add to `PermissionSeeder.php` in the appropriate group
2. Assign defaults to roles (owner gets all automatically)
3. Add `->middleware('permission:your.slug')` to the route in `api.php`
4. Add `permission: 'your.slug'` to the nav item in `Layout.tsx`
5. Wrap the route in `<PermissionGuard>` in `App.tsx`
6. Run `php artisan db:seed --class=PermissionSeeder`

### Owner Permission Assignment

Owners can grant/revoke specific permissions per user via the Settings page:
- `grantPermission(slug, grantedBy)` — Creates user-level override (granted=true)
- `revokePermission(slug, grantedBy)` — Creates user-level override (granted=false)
- `resetPermission(slug)` — Removes override, falls back to role default

